If I embedd an image in my README.md (for example my TeamCity build status icon) the image is not rendered, only a placeholder appears.

The code used in the README.md:

{code}
#!markdown
![Build Status](https://teamcity.wegtam.com/TeamCity/app/rest/builds/buildType:%28id:bt5%29/statusIcon)
{code}

Maybe it is of interest that the README.md is located in a private repository.

From a customer support case:

bq. I&#x27;ve got an issue with TOC inside a page in a directory. On page [1] I have placed a <<toc>> element and I expected it to list all headings in the current page. However instead of:


bq. {code}
https://bitbucket.org/USER/REPO/wiki/Examples/TEST#!valid-examples
{code}


bq. I get links simmilar to:


bq. {code}
https://bitbucket.org/USER/REPO/wiki/Examples/Examples/TEST#!valid-examples
{code}


bq. This means there is an extra "Examples" part.

When attemkpting to change an email address, user&#x27;s will sometimes receive a message like

{code}
user@domain.com is unavailable.
{code}

This message could be better worded as

{code}
The email address user@domain.com is already in use by another user.
{code}

This would minimise confusion.

Its impossible to easily link to a non-existant wiki page, then follow that link and create it, as it usually works for wikis. Lets say we define a link in Creole syntax:

{code}
#!creole
[[My Page]]
{code}

This will create a link to: wiki/My_Page, but such page will report 404. Another problem is that when I try to create this page manually (Create link from wiki) and use title "My Page" it gets converted to "My%20Page" so its encoded differently than underscore used by Creole linking.

These two things make it really hard to quickly create pages on wiki, unless I&#x27;m doing something wrong.
